    <entry>
      <title>Complexity Analysis, Learning Report</title>
      <link href="/2018/01/05/algorithms/complexity_analysis_learning_report/"/>
      <url>/2018/01/05/algorithms/complexity_analysis_learning_report/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<blockquote><p>I need note this, by writing the mathematical formulas by hands, I can retain them.<br><a id="more"></a></p></blockquote><p>The best way to master these materials is through analyzing the real problems, and think them repetitively.</p><p>An illustration image of asymptotic notations involved in discussion.</p><p><img src="/blog-images/asymptotic-notation.png" alt="Example"></p><p>Here, I need review the three notations in the asymptotic analysis of algorithms,</p><p>First, <script type="math/tex">\Theta</script> - notation</p><p>Definition:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\Theta(g(n)) = \{f(n) : there\;exist\;positive\;constants\;c_{1},c_{2},and\;n_{0}\;such\;that\\0 \leq c_{1}g(n) \leq f(n) \leq c_{2}g(n)\;for\;all\;n \geq n_{0}\}.</script><p>Second, <script type="math/tex">O</script> - notation</p><p>Definition:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">O(g(n)) = \{f(n) : there\;exist\;positive\;constants\;c\;and\;n_{0}\;such\;that\\0 \leq f(n) \leq cg(n)\;for\;all\;n \geq n_{0}\}.</script><p>Third, <script type="math/tex">\Omega</script> - notation</p><p>Definition:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\Omega(g(n)) = \{f(n) : there\;exist\;positive\;constants\;c\;and\;n_{0}\;such\;that\\0 \leq cg(n) \leq f(n)\;for\;all\;n \geq n_{0}\}.</script><p>Other notations in lectures,</p><p>Fourth, <script type="math/tex">o</script> - notation</p><p>Definition:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">o(g(n)) = \{f(n) : for\;any\;positive\;constant\;c > 0,\;there\;exists\;a\;constant\;n_{0} > 0\;such\;that\\0 \leq f(n) < cg(n)\;for\;all\;n \geq n_{0}\}.</script><p>Another popular way to illustrate this,</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\lim_{x\to\infty} \frac{f(n)}{g(n)} = 0</script><p>Fifth, <script type="math/tex">\omega</script> - notation</p><p>Definition:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\omega(g(n)) = \{f(n) : for\;any\;positive\;constant\;c > 0,\;there\;exists\;a\;constant\;n_{0} > 0\;such\;that\\0 \leq cg(n) < f(n)\;for\;all\;n \geq n_{0}\}.</script><p>Another popular way to illustrate this,</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\lim_{x\to\infty} \frac{f(n)}{g(n)} = \infty</script><p>Great way to draw an analogy between the asymptotic comparsion of two functions <script type="math/tex">f</script> and <script type="math/tex">g</script> and comparison of two real numbers <script type="math/tex">a</script> and <script type="math/tex">b</script>:</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">f(n) = \Theta(g(n))\;is\;like\;a = b,\\f(n) = O(g(n))\;is\;like\;a \leq b,\\f(n) = \Omega(g(n))\;is\;like\;a \geq b,\\f(n) = o(g(n))\;is\;like\;a < b,\\f(n) = \omega(g(n))\;is\;like\;a > b.</script>]]></content>
      
      
      
    </entry>
    
    
  
  
